Marvell Technology Group Ltd (MRVL.O) Price Target
Unchanged Impact to our thesis
Modest shortfall Financial results versus consensus
Modest revision lower Direction of next 12- month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research
We aren't surprised at lumpiness, but we are surprised that the ASIC full year continues to fall even as Trainium builds strengthen elsewhere. Other parts of the business remain strong.

2025 Trainium revenues continue to disappoint, as our revenue per unit estimate was still likely too high even after earlier disappointment Optical strong, recovery in base business, and will see some recovery in Trainium in the Jan qtr Positive longer term ASIC commentary but expectations management has been a challenge For the 3rd consecutive quarter we were too positive with our preview, and our enthusiasm is limited; stay EW.

ASIC revenues once again fell short of high initial expectations. The quarter and guide was in- line when accounting for the sale of their auto ethernet business, but the data center business disappeared vs. our expectation for strong optics on top of a steady XPU ramp. Once again, the XPU revenue disappointed and is expected to be down sequentially in 3Q, offsetting optical strength and resulting in a flat sequential data center guide for 3Q. Al revenue now comprises \(90\%\) of the data center segment, coming to \(\) 1.34\(2mn in the quarter, though we note that this includes storage which we have heard from our checks is quite strong. Marvell guided to double digit optical growth next quarter, as Marvell continues to benefit from their strong market position.

Marvell's ASIC business near term is principally driven by Amazon Trainium builds, which remain strong, but our full year revenue for MRVL ASIC keeps coming down, which is puzzling. (Amazon is covered by Brian Nowak). After the reset earlier this year, we expected to be past the expectations headwinds. However, the company cited lumpiness in the revenue ramp and now expects digestion in 3Q

with a strong recovery in 4Q. They cited this is mostly timing issues related to when the customer builds are occurring, and they still expect the 2H to grow vs. the 1H. This is inconsistent with what we have heard from the supply chain, and we are surprised at the pause in 3Q. We are now modeling the data center flat \(q / q\) in OctQ, and growing \(6\%\) in the JanQ. This brings our CY2025 data center revenue to \(\) 6.002bn\(down from\) \ \(6.193bn\) previously, and with ASIC likely at about \(25\%\) of that, Trainium is likely less than \(\) 1.5\(bn, implying ASPs at\) \ \(1500\) or less; even with HBM removed, we are surprised that the revenue has fallen that far.

Marvell's non- data center portfolio showed signs of recovery. Enterprise networking and carrier infrastructure revenues grew \(2\%\) sequentially, supported by normalized inventories and adoption of refreshed products portfolio. They guided carrier and enterprise networking to grow \(30\%\) next quarter, ahead of our estimates. Consumer revenue rebounded sharply \((+84\% q / q)\) on gaming demand, though management expects modest sequential declines next quarter. Auto and industrial was flat \(q / q\) and will incorporate the divestiture next quarter, bringing revenue down \(\) 35\(mn. While not the primary growth engine, trends here seem steady.

Details on the quarter: Marvell reported July quarter revenue of \(\) 2.006bn\(up 6\%\) \(q / q\) and \(58\% y / y\) below the street at \(\) 2.010bn\(and our estimate of\) \ \(2.012bn\) . On a segment basis, Data Center revenue came in at \(\) 1.49bn\(up 3.5\% q / q\) and \(69.2\% y / y\) Carrier at \(\) 130.1mn\(down 6.0\% q / q\) and up \(71.4\% y / y\) , Enterprise Networking at \(\) 193.6mn\(up 9.1\% q / q\) and \(28.2\% y / y\) , Auto Industrial at \(\) 76mn\(up 0.4\% q / q\) and down \(0.3\% y / y\) , and Consumer at \(\) 115.9mn\(up 83.7\% q / q\) and \(30.4\% y / y\) . Gross margin of \(59.4\%\) was slightly below the street and our estimate of \(59.5\%\) . EPS of \(\) 0.67\(came in - line with the street and our estimate of\) \ \(0.67\) .

Guidance and changes to estimates: October quarter revenue was guided to \(\) 2.060bn\(at the midpoint (up 3\% q / q\) and \(36\% y / y\) ), below the street at \(\) 2.111bn\(and in - line with our estimate of\) \ \(2.067bn\) . Gross margin was guided to \(59.8\%\) , above the street at \(59.4\%\) and our estimate of \(59.3\%\) . EPS was guided to \(\) 0.74\(, slightly above the street and our estimate of\) \ \(0.72\) . Our numbers are broadly unchanged since we were already below the street and upside from carrier and enterprise is somewhat offsetting the lower data center revenue. For FY2026, we model revenue/GM/EPS of \(\) 8.1bn/59.6\%/2.79\(vs. our prior\) \ \(8.1bn/59.4\% /\) \ \(2.75\) , and for FY2027 we model \(\) 9bn/58.9\%/3.10\(vs.\) \ \(9bn/58.6\% /\) \ \(3.12\) prior.

Thoughts on the stock: Marvell has had a good year fundamentally, with growth of about \(60\%\) in the first half of the fiscal year. But expectations for ASIC were higher, given management commentary earlier in the year, and the reaction to that has been to move longer term expectations even higher. We do believe that Marvell can grow the Amazon business next year, including XPU attach - the smaller the revenue in 2025, the lower that bar is - but the next major ASIC project could be large, but there are no guarantees. We keep suggesting that strength in optical will drive numbers higher despite ASIC revenues being lower, but we have been wrong about that for three quarters and our confidence is a bit lower near term. We stay EW.

We lower our PT to from \(\) 80\(to\) \ \(76\) , based on \(34x\) CY2026 MW EPS of \(\) 2.23\(includes stock based compensation), which is about\) 23x\(non - GAAP EPS. We lower our multiple from\) 35x\(to\) 34x\(as our enthusiasm for the ASIC story lessens.
Attractive growth capability but valuation leaves us EW

The company has Al related opportunity, primarily the higher speed elements of the Inphi optical businesses (PAM4 and 400ZR), and longer term cloud custom silicon. We do expect this growth to play out, in particular on the optical side, and we expect MRVL to outgrow data center spending overall. We remain EW given valuation as well as high stock compensation expense that weighs on enthusiasm.

- CY26 Revenue comes in at \(\) 9.6\(bn
- Marvell's AI opportunity comes in larger than expected, helping drive upside to revenue estimates as well as drive multiple expansion
- The company hits on a number of cloud growth opportunities that drive the multiple higher
- We expect CY26 revenue to come in at \(\) 9bn\$
- MW GM of \(58.3\%\) in 2026 (includes SBC)
- Storage and enterprise data center remain weak, with little line of sight for a recovery
- Networking continues to be a headwind, as inventory both at customers and in the channel continue to offset tailwinds in the custom ASIC business
- Stock overshoots to the downside closer to its tangible book value
